Dear Annamalai and Seenivasan,

I have reviewed both the 2 April and the 10 April versions of the Sales 
Order FSD from the QA mail ID. I want to give both of you a clear 
picture of what has improved, what still needs to be done, and what each 
of you must action before this document can proceed.

*On the improvement from version 1 to version 2 — Annamalai*

*This is a substantial revision and the effort is visible.* Between 2 
April and today, ten sections that were either absent or inadequate have 
been brought to a proper standard. Let me be specific.

Section 3 (Field Rules) is new and covers 25 fields with mandatory 
flags, data types, lengths, defaults, and notes. Section 4 (Validation 
Rules) is now correctly structured into four categories — Pre-Add, 
Header, Line Entry, and Customer-Specific — with error messages inline. 
This was entirely absent in version 1. Section 6 (TC Framework) is now 
present and correctly states that the Sale Order form does not trigger 
stock movements or accounting entries at the point of order creation — 
TC activation happens downstream at despatch and invoice. This is the 
correct understanding and it protects the SPINRISE developer from 
building the wrong integration point.

Section 7 (Common Module Dependencies) now analyses Spinmod.bas, 
modGeneral.bas, and clsCrystal.cls at the function level. Section 8 (DB 
Operations) now documents both KSP_LSALES_SALEORDER and 
KSP_TCSAmountCheckLSales with their business rules. Section 9 (Error 
Messages) is entirely new — 39 exact messages with trigger conditions. 
Sections 12 (SPINRISE Recommendations), 13 (IST Review Questions), and 
14 (Summary Scorecard) are all new additions. This is a complete 
restructuring of the document and it is aligned with the v2 template.

*This is the level of quality that should have been in the first 
submission.* That said, the first submission was made on 2 April — eight 
days before the current date — and Seenivasan had eight days to review 
it and provide feedback. No IST feedback was provided. I will address 
that separately below.

*What still needs to be completed before this FSD can proceed to IST review*

*1. Stage 0 confirmation is absent from the document header.*
The Document Identity table does not record Stage 0 completion status, 
the line count before and after cleaning, or TL-Dev sign-off. The RMI 
module FSD correctly showed '12,198 lines cleaned to 11,066 lines' in 
its header. This document shows only '453 KB' as the file size with no 
cleaning record. Annamalai: please confirm with TL-Dev Sasi whether 
Stage 0 has been completed on frmcontract.frm, add the line count before 
and after, and add TL-Dev Sasi's sign-off to the document header.

*2. CustID-based hardcoding — has Stage 0 actually resolved this?*
Section 11 (Customer Variations) lists 11 customer-specific behaviours. 
Most of these are described against customer names rather than ig_param 
configuration flags. The Summary Scorecard in Section 14 itself rates 
Customer Configurability at 3 out of 5 with the note 'mostly hard-coded 
with if-then-else rather than configuration-table driven.' This is the 
same issue that required extensive correction in the PO module's PR 
form, which had 13 hardcoded CustID blocks that Stage 0 had to remove 
and replace with po_para flags. The question for Annamalai is direct: 
has Stage 0 removed the CustID-based conditional blocks (SLVSM, SARANYA, 
CHERAN, SKY, SKS, KUMARAGIRI, LMW, JTCL, SCM/JAT) from the cleaned form, 
and replaced them with ig_param flag-driven behaviour? If not, Stage 0 
is not complete for this form. SPINRISE cannot be built from a form that 
still contains hardcoded customer ID checks.

*3. Three stored procedures require code submission and Follow-up Prompt 
B analysis.*
Section 8.4 documents KSP_LSALES_SALEORDER and Section 8.5 documents 
KSP_TCSAmountCheckLSales at a business-rule description level. Section 
5.5 references a third SP, Ksp_PendingOrderVal, used in the credit limit 
calculation. None of the three have been analysed from the actual SQL 
code. The rate calculation inside KSP_LSALES_SALEORDER, the union logic 
and threshold comparison inside KSP_TCSAmountCheckLSales, and the 
pending order value query inside Ksp_PendingOrderVal must all be 
submitted to Claude using Follow-up Prompt B from the v2 guide. The SP 
analysis must come from the code, not from a description of what the SP 
is intended to do. Please obtain all three SP codes from SQL Server 
Management Studio and run Follow-up Prompt B on each.

*4. The audit trail write is missing from the Save Sequence.*
Section 8.3 documents the Save Sequence in seven steps. Notably absent 
is the INSERT into ig_trans_log_sales, which was documented in detail in 
version 1 of this document including the exact SQL with IP address, 
hostname, and user ID. This is a regression — the audit trail write 
existed in v1 and has been lost in v2. Please add it as a step in 
Section 8.3, with the field mapping.

*5. The document number race condition must be flagged as a Critical 
Defect.*
Section 12 Recommendation 4 correctly identifies that IG_DOCCONTROL 
document numbering should be replaced with a sequence service. But the 
underlying risk is not stated as a defect. The current code reads MAX+1 
from IG_DOCCONTROL without a lock, which means concurrent saves from two 
users can produce duplicate order numbers. The RMI PO FSD correctly 
flagged this as CD-2 with an explicit SPINRISE fix. Please add this as a 
Critical Defect entry — the same pattern exists here and the same 
UPDLOCK-based sequence fix applies.

*6. Section 11 needs SPINRISE configuration flag names and defaults.*
The RMI PO FSD mapped each RM_PARAM flag to a SPINRISE config name with 
a recommended default value. The Sales Order Section 11 describes what 
each customer variation does but does not say how SPINRISE should handle 
it. For each of the 11 variation rows, please add two columns: the 
SPINRISE config parameter name, and the recommended default for a new 
customer installation.

*7. Auto-email flow not sufficiently documented.*
Section 1 correctly lists auto-email as a capability. Section 12 
references it. But the trigger logic (CheckAutoMail reads 
ig_param.AutoMail flag), the export path (Sales_PrintSMTP exports 
Crystal to KALFOLDERDATA), and the CDO SMTP configuration (server, port, 
SSL, credentials from pp_divmas) are not in Section 8 or Section 7 at 
the level needed for SPINRISE migration. In SPINRISE, the email flow 
will be replaced by a transactional email service — but the trigger 
conditions, the recipient (customer email from fa_slmas), and the 
attachment format must be documented so the SPINRISE developer knows 
exactly when and how to send the email.

*For Seenivasan — on your role in this review*

*Seenivasan, I want to be direct.* Annamalai submitted the version 1 FSD 
to you on 2 April. That was eight days ago. You have not provided a 
single IST review comment on that document. Your mail today asks 
Annamalai for a 'revised FSD' without telling him what needs to be 
revised. *That is not how the IST review process works.
*
The IST reviewer's job is to read the document, answer the IST review 
questions in Section 13, and flag any domain-level inaccuracies in the 
business logic, validation rules, and customer variations. The developer 
revises based on IST feedback. *You have that sequence reversed.*

Version 2 of the FSD has arrived, with Section 13 now containing 12 
structured IST questions. *Your responsibility is to answer all 12 of 
those questions directly in the document.* The questions cover credit 
limit override authority (IST-1), agent mandatory setup (IST-2), offer 
rate flag trigger (IST-3), CSM integration status (IST-4), TCS threshold 
(IST-5), JW rules (IST-6), IG_INSBODT vs IG_BODT (IST-7), rate decimal 
configuration (IST-8), cancellation policy (IST-9), report footer 
variants (IST-10), multi-division orders (IST-11), and auto-mail system 
(IST-12).

*Please complete your IST review of Section 13 and send your responses 
to Annamalai so the document can be updated. Tomorrow is the Saturday 
review meeting. I expect a status update on M03 that shows IST 
engagement, not silence.*


*Overall assessment*

The improvement from version 1 to version 2 represents exactly the 
standard the v2 guide is designed to produce. Annamalai has used the 
eight days since version 1 productively and the document is now 
structurally sound. The seven items above are what stands between this 
document and the formal IST review chain.

*Annamalai,* address items 1 through 7 above. The most urgent are Stage 
0 confirmation (item 1) and the CustID hardcoding question (item 2), 
because those determine whether the form is migration-ready at all.

*Seenivasan,* answer the IST questions. The developer has done his part.

Regards,
T. Mani

cc: TL-Dev Sasi, PM Saravanan, TL-IST Palanivel

